Optics in the mid-wave infrared (MWIR or mid-IR) wavelengths, particularly the atmospheric transmission window of 3 to 5 &mu;m, has been a topic of active research. Historically, the need for sources and detectors operating in this range has been primarily driven by military applications such as Light Detection And Ranging (LIDAR) and infrared countermeasures. Over the past decade, mid-IR photonics has found a host of civilian applications, e.g., Fourier transform infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy, remote chemical and biological sensing and free-space optical communications. More recently, clinical applications have also emerged. For example, tissue photoablation by targeting the mid-IR resonant absorption peaks in water, the amide bonds in collagen and other tissue chromospheres have been pursued. Also, environmental and industrial applications for hydrocarbon detection from vehicles, oil fields and industrial smoke stacks are of interest. These applications would have not been possible without successes in high-performance mid-IR optical sources and detectors, as reviewed below. However, most current systems are based on assemblage of discrete components, i.e., true integration is lacking. Device miniaturization and monolithic integration would hence be a great advancement in the field of mid-IR photonics, which is the goal of this program.

This program aims at transforming the emerging field of mid-IR silicon photonics by demonstrating a range of novel and related passive and active (nonlinear) integrated photonic devices and circuits.  Several significant outcomes were achieved and pubished in numerous contributed and invited conference and journal papers, as well as two patents. The significant results can be summarized as:

1) The first demosntrarion of silicon-on-nitride waveguides;

2) The first demosntrarion of silicon on lithium-niobate waveguides and modulators;

3) The first demosntrarion of all-silicon suspended and anchored membrane waveguides;

4) Demosntrarion of ultrabroadand single-polarization waveguides in T-shaped waveguides;

5) Demonstration of topographically-anisotropic photonics. 

